n pattern"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMalignant cells typically demonstrate several key histological features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased mitotic figures\u003C/strong\u003E reflect uncontrolled cell division and is a hallmark of cancer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased nuclear size\u003C/strong\u003E is not typical - malignant cells usually show enlarged, irregular nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular nuclear membranes\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of normal cells - cancer cells show irregular nuclear membranes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced nucleoli\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - malignant cells typically have prominent, often multiple nucleoli\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUniform chromatin pattern\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in normal cells - cancer cells show coarse, irregular chromatin\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther features of malignancy include loss of cellular polarity, altered nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratios, and nuclear pleomorphism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignant cells show increased mitotic activity, nuclear pleomorphism, loss of polarity, and altered nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratios.","Key histological features of malignancy include abnormal chromatin patterns, prominent nucleoli, and irregular nuclear membranes."],"references":["Hanahan D, Weinberg RA. Hallmarks of cancer: the next generation. Cell. 2011 Mar 4;144(5):646-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2011.02.013. PMID: 21376230.","Cooper GM. The Cell: A Molecular Approach. 2nd edition. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates; 2000. The Development and Causes of Cancer. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9963/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"item